id="post-3366" class="post-3366 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-mind-space tag-relax tag-work"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/07/12/keep-sane-by-not-working/" title="Permalink to Keep Sane by not Working" rel="bookmark">Keep Sane by not Working</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2012/07/12 4:32 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/07/12/keep-sane-by-not-working/" title="Keep Sane by not Working" rel="bookmark">2012/07/12 4:32 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Thanks to modern technology it can be really easy to always be checking email and taking calls. This is great for some circumstances but it&#8217;s always important to take a break from being always-connected to work. In fact, it can be good for you!</p><blockquote><p>Another trick: simply ask yourself &#8220;will anything bad really happen between 5pm and 6am if I turn my back on my inboxes completely?&#8221;<br
/> To save your own life, create your own list of &#8220;tricks&#8221; and of rules to impose on yourself. Some of mine that work:<br
/> • Switch gears: When tired of &#8220;project A,&#8221; switch to something else on the list &#8212; easier, different, faster-paced or (gasp) fun. Changing rhythm is restorative and you return to the tougher project fresher in an amazingly short time.<br
/> • Change chairs and media &#8212; draft that important thing in (gasp) longhand in a club chair or on a sofa.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.cnn.com/2012/07/12/opinion/switch-off-work-dorf/index.html?utm_source=feedburner&#038;utm_medium=feed&#038;utm_campaign=Feed:+rss/cnn_latest+(RSS:+Most+Recent)">Read more.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-3366-5383e6f6601d5' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=3366&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-3366-5383e6f6601d5' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-3366-5383e6f6601d5'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
